// A lambda whose inferred return type is byte must declare it: the
// runtime decides map's compact-vs-boxed result by the callback's
// DECLARED return type (an omitted lambda return stores nothing in
// ClosureData, indistinguishable from void), so an inferred-only byte
// return would checker-type the map result []byte while the runtime
// builds a boxed list — str() faulted on every spelling below before
// this rule. The rule is at the lambda, not the map site, because the
// closure can launder through a fn-typed variable no map-site check can
// see. Spell the return type: fn(x byte) byte { return x }.
fn main() {
    b := []byte{104, 105}
    c := b.map(fn(x byte) { x })
    print(len(c))
    d := []byte{}.map(fn(x) { x })
    print(len(d))
    xs := [104, 105]
    e := xs.map(fn(x int) { byte(x) })
    print(len(e))
    g := fn(x byte) { x }
    f := b.map(g)
    print(len(f))
}
